course: main course
---

Halve @brioche buns{6}. Place half the @roasted garlic-herb butter{1oz} in a small
#microwave-safe bowl{}; microwave until melted, ~{30%seconds}. Stir in half the
@Mike's Hot Honey®{1%oz}.

Tear or roughly chop @pulled pork{8%oz} into smaller pieces. Pat @chicken cutlets{10%oz} dry with
#paper towels{}; season all over with @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Form
@ground beef{20%oz} into four equal-size patties, each slightly wider than a bun;
season generously with @salt{} and @black pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #pan{} over medium-high heat. Add pork,
@classic BBQ sauce{4%oz}, and @water{3/4%cup}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until
reduced and thickened, ~{4-6%minutes}. Taste and season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}.
Keep covered until ready to serve.

== Grill Method ==

Heat a well-oiled #grill{} or #grill pan{} to medium-high heat. Add beef patties and
chicken; cook patties to desired doneness and chicken until cooked through (we
suggest ~{3-5%minutes} per side for both, but grills can vary). In the last ~{2%minutes}
of cooking, brush chicken with honey garlic butter and top with @gouda cheese{2%slices};
top patties with @shredded cheddar cheese{4%oz}. Cover and cook until cheese melts.
Add buns; toast until golden.

== Stovetop Method ==

Toast buns. Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a second large pan over medium-high heat.
Add beef patties and chicken; cook patties to desired doneness, ~{3-5%minutes} per
side, and chicken until cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes} per side. In the last
~{2%minutes} of cooking, brush chicken with honey garlic butter and top with gouda;
top patties with cheddar. Cover and cook until cheese melts.

== Assembly ==

Spread cut sides of two buns with remaining garlic herb butter and fill with chicken;
drizzle with remaining hot honey to taste. Fill two buns with beef patties. Fill
remaining buns with BBQ pork.

> Whether you're celebrating Dad or the Fourth of July, nothing beats a cookout.
> Grilling is highly recommended for the ultimate summer experience and flavor,
> but cooking on the stove top will do, too.

